In [50]:
#What is the difference between label encoding and one hot encoding, and when should you use one
#over the other?

# - label encoding us assugbed a unique ineger based on alphabetical ordering and one-hot encoding 
#  just create dummies variables, theres no order in one-hot encoding

# - We use label encoding when the categorical feature is ordinal, the number of categories is 
#   quite large as one-hot encoding can lead to high memory consumption

# - We us one-hot encoding when the categorical feature is not ordinal (not inorder), the number of 
#   categorical features is less so one-hot encoding can be effectively applied
In [51]:
#What is multicollinearity, and why do we care about it when creating models? How can we check to see
#if there's significant multicollinearity in our data?

# - Multiconllinearity means that several variables are essentially measuring the same thing. We care
#   about multicollinearity when creating model because the model result can fluctuate. We can check
#   the multicollinearity by using heatmap. If server collinearity issue exists(e.g correlation > 0.8
#   between 2 variables)
In [52]:
#Why is scaling data important?

# - Scaling data is essential because it calculate the distances between data. This is crucial for when
#   working with KNN because the KNN classifier predicts the class of a given test observation by
#   identifying the obserbations that are nearts to it, the scale of the variables matters. If this is
#   not taken into account, any variables that are on a large sclae will have a much larger effect on the
#   distance between the observation, and hence on the KNN classifierm than variables that are on a small
#   scale
In [53]:
#For the two different models that you named earlier, are they using a parametric or 
#non- parametric learning algorithms? Whats the difference?

# - Both model decision trees and random forest uses non-parametric learning algorithm. 
# - Non-parametric method means that there are no underlying assumptions about the distribution of
#  the erros or the data. It basically means that the model is constructed based on the observed data

# - Parametric method have a finite number of parameters while non-parametric have infinite

from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(heart_data.drop('output', axis = 1),
                                                    heart_data['output'], test_size = 0.3, random_state=10)
In [62]:
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
model = RandomForestClassifier(max_depth=5)
model.fit(X_train, y_train)
